  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use natural transformations only when you already have:\nTwo functors F,G:C→DF, G:C \\to D between the same categories. A morphism in DD for each object of CC. A requirement that these morphisms are compatible with all morphisms in CC. ¶Definitions A natural transformation η:F⇒G\\eta:F \\Rightarrow G assigns to each object AA in CC a morphism ηA:F(A)→G(A)\\eta_A: F(A) \\to G(A) in DD, such that for every morphism f:A→Bf:A \\to B in CC, G(f)∘ηA=ηB∘F(f). G(f) \\circ \\eta_A = \\eta_B \\circ F(f). ¶Vocabulary (plain language) Component: the specific morphism ηA\\eta_A for an object AA. Naturality: the condition that the square above commutes for every morphism. ¶Symbols used η:F⇒G\\eta:F \\Rightarrow G: a natural transformation. ηA\\eta_A: the component at AA. ¶Intuition A natural transformation is a systematic way to transform one functor into another without breaking structure. It says that the transformation is compatible with every morphism in the source category.\n",
  "name": "Natural Transformations",
